<HL>
   Who's News:
   Oglebay Norton Co.
   Gives Green New Post
</HL>
<DATE>
09/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   OGLE WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
</IN>
<LP>
   CLEVELAND -- Oglebay Norton Co. directors named R. Thomas
Green Jr. executive vice president, making him the leading
candidate to be the next president of the mining and
lake-shipping concern.
   Mr. Green, 53 years old, joined the company in 1965 and
has headed both the company's silica and iron ore mining
businesses. His latest title was vice president, iron ore
operations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Oglebay's president and chief executive officer, Renold D.
Thompson, is 64. Courtney Burton, chairman, is 77.
   Oglebay's largest business is lake shipping. It owns 13
Great Lakes ships and has agreed to purchase two others. The
company operates an iron ore mine and pellet processing plant
at Eveleth, Minn., which it owns jointly with steel company
partners. It produces silica for glass, paint and other uses;
mines coal, and manufactures products for the iron and steel
industry. In 1989, Oglebay earned $5 million, or $1.94 a
share, on revenue of $165.3 million.
</TEXT>
